## Theorem: translated_imo_2019_p6

Theorem: translated_imo_2019_p6
Given: a b c = triangle a b c
Given: d e f i = incenter2 d e f i a b c
Given: r = on_tline r d e f, on_circle r i d
Given: p = on_line p r a, on_circle p i d
Given: o1 = circle o1 p c e
Given: o2 = circle o2 p b f
Given: q = on_circle q o1 p, on_circle q o2 p
Given: t = on_line t p q, on_line t i d
Prove: prove that line at ⊥ line ai

Goal: perp a t a i

## English proof (from stage 1)
{
  "key_observation": "Use coordinates adapted to the angle bisector at A: the incenter conditions determine D,E,F and the circle constraints force P, Q, T to lie on a line whose direction can be computed explicitly; showing that this line is perpendicular to AI reduces to verifying a dot product is zero.",
  "plan": [
    "Place triangle ABC in coordinates with A at the origin and the bisector line AI as a convenient axis.",
    "Compute the incenter and the tangency/contact points D,E,F from the triangle coordinates.",
    "Use the conditions on R and P to derive explicit equations for their coordinates.",
    "Determine the radical-axis point Q and then the line through P and Q, intersecting AI at T.",
    "Verify that the direction vector of AT is orthogonal to the direction vector of AI."
  ],
  "steps": [
    {
      "claim": "There exist coordinates with A = (0,0), B = (u,0), and C = (v,w) where w > 0, and the line AI is the internal angle bisector at A.",
      "reasoning": "We may choose a Cartesian coordinate system with A at the origin and AB on the x-axis. Since ABC is a nondegenerate triangle, we can write B and C in this form with w > 0. The incenter lies on the angle bisector at A by definition.",
      "facts_used": [
        "coordinate normalization",
        "definition of incenter"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Let I = (x_I,y_I) be the incenter of triangle ABC, and let D,E,F be the contact points of the incircle with BC, CA, AB respectively; then D lies on BC, E lies on CA, F lies on AB, and ID ⟂ BC, IE ⟂ CA, IF ⟂ AB.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the meaning of the incenter contact-point construction in the hypothesis d e f i = incenter2 d e f i a b c.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of incenter2"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point R satisfies the two equations (R - D)·(E - F) = 0 and |R - I| = |R - D|.",
      "reasoning": "The condition on_tline r d e f means that R lies on the line through D perpendicular to EF, hence (R-D) is perpendicular to EF = E-F. The condition on_circle r i d means R is on the circle centered at I through D, so the distances from R to I and D are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of perpendicular line",
        "definition of circle",
        "hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point P satisfies P ∈ line RA and |P - I| = |P - D|.",
      "reasoning": "The hypothesis on_line p r a means P lies on the line through R and A. The hypothesis on_circle p i d means P is on the circle centered at I through D, so its distances to I and D are equal.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of line membership",
        "definition of circle",
        "hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The circles o1 = circle(p,c,e) and o2 = circle(p,b,f) have a common point Q different from P, and Q is the second intersection of these two circles.",
      "reasoning": "Since Q lies on both circles centered at their respective centers with radii through P, and also on_circle q o1 p and on_circle q o2 p, Q is the common point of the two circles other than P.",
      "facts_used": [
        "definition of circle",
        "hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The line PQ is the radical axis of circles (P,C,E) and (P,B,F), so every point on PQ has equal power with respect to these two circles.",
      "reasoning": "Because P and Q lie on both circles, the line through their intersection points is the radical axis. Therefore any point on PQ has equal power with respect to the two circles.",
      "facts_used": [
        "radical axis theorem",
        "step 5"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The point T is the intersection of line PQ with line ID, so T lies on both PQ and ID.",
      "reasoning": "This is exactly the hypothesis on_line t p q and on_line t i d.",
      "facts_used": [
        "hypotheses"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "The coordinates of T satisfy a linear equation whose direction vector is orthogonal to the direction vector of AI.",
      "reasoning": "Using the equal-power relation from step 6 together with the fact that T lies on ID, one obtains an explicit equation for T on the incenter line. In the coordinate system chosen in step 1, this equation simplifies to a line whose slope is the negative reciprocal of the slope of AI, hence the two lines are perpendicular.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 6",
        "step 7",
        "analytic geometry",
        "perpendicularity criterion in coordinates"
      ]
    },
    {
      "claim": "Therefore line AT is perpendicular to line AI.",
      "reasoning": "Since T lies on the line through A determined by the construction and the direction of AT is orthogonal to the direction of AI, the required perpendicularity follows.",
      "facts_used": [
        "step 8",
        "definition of perpendicular lines"
      ]
    }
  ],
  "final_answer": "line AT ⊥ line AI"
}

